# Leong Woon Lam _v_ Muhammad Harunal Rashid bin Mohamed Razif and another  

### \[2022\] SGDC 189

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Court Suit No 1216 of 2020</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">29 August 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Lim Mei Yee Elaine</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Deepak Natverial (Crown Juris Law LLC) (instructed), Tiwary Anuradha (Everest Law LLC) for the plaintiff; Chua Tong Nung Edwin, Cassandra Kang (Lawrence Chua Practice LLC) for the defendants.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Leong Woon Lam — Muhammad Harunal Rashid bin Mohamed Razif — Leong Best Food House Pte Ltd</td></tr></tbody></table>

Tort – Negligence – Breach of duty

Tort – Negligence – Contributory negligence

29 August 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### District Judge Lim Mei Yee Elaine:

1       On 7 April 2018 at around 8pm or 9pm, a collision occurred in the vicinity of the cross junction of Woodlands Avenue 9 and Woodlands Ave 4 (the “Junction”), between the plaintiff pedestrian and motorcycle FBJ 7482 (the “motorcycle”) which was ridden by the 1st defendant as an employee of the 2nd defendant. The plaintiff was crossing Woodlands Avenue 4 at the material time. The plaintiff commenced this action for losses arising from injuries he had sustained in the accident.

2       The trial before me was solely on the issue of liability. After considering the evidence and the parties’ submissions, I find the defendants wholly liable for the accident. These are the reasons for my decision.

## Undisputed facts

3       A Google Earth photograph of the roads leading into and out of the Junction, taken in May 2018, is reproduced below.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) Parties agreed that the photograph accurately portrays the number of lanes and the markings on the roads at the time of the accident.

4       For ease of understanding, I have marked in the photograph:(a) the road names, (b) the pedestrian crossing at which the plaintiff alleges the collision had occurred, and (c) the general direction in which the plaintiff was crossing Woodlands Avenue 4 at the time of the accident.

![](data:image;base64,)

5       For the avoidance of doubt, all lane numbers referred to in this judgment are numbered on the basis that the leftmost lane is the 1st lane, the lane to the right of the 1st lane is the 2nd lane, the lane to the right of the 2nd lane is the 3rd lane, and so on.

6       As seen from the above Google Earth photograph, before the Junction, there are four lanes along Woodlands Avenue 9 in the direction of Gambas Avenue. The rightmost lane – the 4th lane – is only for vehicles turning right into Woodlands Avenue 4. The 1st to 3rd lanes are for vehicles going straight across the Junction: they link up to the three lanes along Woodlands Avenue 9 after the Junction.

7       The collision occurred in the 3rd lane of Woodlands Avenue 9 after the Junction, though it is disputed whether it happened at the pedestrian crossing or slightly after the pedestrian crossing. Both the plaintiff and the 1st defendant lost consciousness upon impact, were seriously injured, and were conveyed to Khoo Teck Puat Hospital (“KTPH”) for treatment.

8       At the material time, the weather was clear, the road was dry, visibility was good as the Junction was well lit, and the traffic lights at the Junction were working.

9       No action was taken by the police against any of the parties in relation to the accident.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

## Summary of the parties’ cases

### The plaintiff’s case

10     The plaintiff’s pleaded case is that he was crossing Woodlands Avenue 4 at the pedestrian crossing, with the pedestrian crossing signal green in his favour, when the motorcycle collided into him.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) The 1st defendant was wholly liable for the collision by reason of his negligence in (a) failing to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road, and to give way to the plaintiff who had the right of way, (b) travelling at an excessive speed, (c) failing to keep a proper lookout and (d) failing to take evasive action to avoid the collision. The 2nd defendant was vicariously liable for the 1st defendant’s negligence.[^4]

11     The plaintiff did not state in his pleadings which direction the motorcycle had come from. He subsequently opined in his affidavit of evidence-in-chief (“AEIC”) that the 1st defendant must have beat the red light signal against him and entered the Junction before colliding into the plaintiff.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)

12     However, at trial, instructed counsel for the plaintiff, Mr Deepak Natverial (“Mr Natverial”), put it to the 1st defendant that he had turned right at the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4 into Woodlands Avenue 9 and collided into the plaintiff. I allowed Mr Deepak to explore this new stance with the 1st defendant as no irremediable prejudice was caused to the defendants: see _Noor Azlin bte Abdul Rahman and another v Changi General Hospital Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] 1 SLR 689</span> (“_Noor Azlin_”) at \[274\]. The defendants had adequate opportunity to respond to this new stance through the evidence given by the 1st defendant on the stand and in their closing submissions.

### The defendants’ case

13     The defendants’ pleaded case is that at the material time, the 1st defendant was travelling along Woodlands Avenue 9. When he reached the Junction, the traffic lights were green in his favour. Thus, he proceeded straight across the Junction. When he was nearing the other side of the Junction, the plaintiff, who was crossing the pedestrian crossing, suddenly stepped into his path.[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) In the premises, the collision was wholly caused or contributed to by the plaintiff’s negligence in (a) crossing the road when the lights were red against pedestrians, (b) failing to give way to the motorcycle, (c) failing to ascertain that traffic was clear before crossing the pedestrian crossing and (d) failing to keep a proper lookout when crossing the pedestrian crossing.[^7]

14     In his AEIC, the 1st defendant elaborated that at the material time, he was on a delivery assignment to Woods Vale condominium, and was traveling on the 3rd lane of Woodlands Avenue 9 when he entered the Junction. However, the 1st defendant departed from his pleaded case by alleging that when he saw the plaintiff in his path, he had already gone past the pedestrian crossing: the plaintiff had not used the pedestrian crossing, but was instead jaywalking without looking out for traffic approaching from the Junction.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) I allowed this departure from the defendants’ pleaded case as no irremediable prejudice was caused to the plaintiff: see _Noor Azlin_ at \[274\]. The plaintiff had adequate opportunity to respond to the defendants’ new stance through his counsel’s cross examination of the 1st defendant and in his closing submissions.

15     In their closing submissions, the defendants concede that the 1st defendant had failed to keep a proper lookout and to take evasive action to avoid the collision. However, they maintain that the plaintiff is substantially liable for the collision as he had crossed the road without keeping a proper lookout and in defiance of the red man, and that the apportionment of liability should be 80% on the plaintiff and 20% on the 1st defendant.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)

### The witnesses

16     The plaintiff’s sole witness was himself.

17     The defendants called three witnesses:

> (a)     the 1st defendant;

> (b)     Mr Chew Chin Tat (“Mr Chew”), an employee of the 2nd defendant and at the material time, the 1st defendant’s supervisor; and

> (c)     Mr Fong Ah Kiew (“Mr Fong”), a representative of ATS Traffic Pte Ltd, the company which operated the traffic light system at the Junction at the material time.

18     Mr Chew and Mr Fong did not witness the accident. Mr Chew’s evidence covered, among other things, (a) the 1st defendant’s work schedule on the day of the accident and the assignment he was on at the material time, (b) Mr Chew’s belief that a Malay couple were independent witnesses to the accident, and (c) the circumstances in which the 1st defendant made his GIA report on 24 April 2018. Mr Fong’s evidence focused mainly on the sequence of operation of the traffic lights at the Junction.

19     The correspondence between the defendants’ solicitors and the traffic police revealed that there was apparently an independent witness to the accident, but he was unwilling to come forward to assist the parties in this Suit and the police was unable to disclose his particulars to the parties.

## Issues to be determined

20     Based on the parties’ respective positions, the following issues arise for determination:

> (a)      Issue 1: Whether the plaintiff has proven his pleaded case that the collision occurred when he was crossing the pedestrian crossing with the pedestrian crossing signal green in his favour.

> (b)      Issue 2: If the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision, whether the 1st defendant was negligent in:

>> (i)       failing to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road, and to give way to the plaintiff; and

>> (ii)       travelling at an excessive speed.

> (c)      Issue 3: If the defendant is found to be negligent, whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent in:

>> (i)       failing to ascertain that traffic was clear before crossing the road; and

>> (ii)       failing to keep a proper lookout when crossing the road.

> (d)      Issue 4: If the plaintiff is found to be contributorily negligent, how should liability for the accident be apportioned between the parties.

## Issue 1: Whether the plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision

### Preliminary question: Burden of proof

21     Before delving into the substance of this issue, I must address a preliminary question arising from the plaintiff’s closing submissions. The question is: which party has the legal burden of proving that the traffic lights were in their favour and that they had the right of way?

22     The plaintiff submits that the legal burden falls squarely on the defendants, based on the authority of _SCT Technologies Pte Ltd v Western Copper Co Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 1 SLR 1471</span> (“_SCT Technologies_”). His argument may be summarised as follows:[^10]

> (a)     The Singapore Court of Appeal in _SCT Technologies_ had approved the principles adopted in _Big Island Construction (HK) Ltd v Wu Yi Development Co Ltd_ \[2015\] HKEC 1232 (“_Big Island_”) for oral loans. In _Big Island_, the plaintiff claimed against the defendant for monies lent pursuant to an alleged oral loan agreement. The defendant admitted receipt of the payments but denied the existence of an oral loan agreement. The Hong Kong court held that the burden of proof laid on the plaintiff to prove the existence of the loan agreement, but if the defendants had raised the defence of payment instead, that would have operated as a confession and avoidance defence for which the defendants would bear the burden of proving the payments.

> (b)     Applying _Big Island_ to the present case, since the plaintiff has shown cogent evidence that the pedestrian lights were in his favour and the defendants have run their defence on the basis that the 1st defendant had the right of way, the defendants bear the burden of proving that the traffic lights were in the 1st defendant’s favour and that the 1st defendant had the right of way.

23     I find this argument to be fundamentally misconceived. It is trite law that each party has the legal burden of proving the material facts in support of its claim or defence, and that the material facts are to be gleaned from the pleadings: see _SCT_ at \[17\].[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11) The plaintiff’s pleaded case is that the 1st defendant was negligent because he had, among other things, failed to stop and wait at the Junction for the plaintiff to safely cross the road using the pedestrian crossing while the green man was illuminated: see \[10\] above. This is a material fact in support of his claim against the defendants: it pertains to the element of breach of the 1st defendant’s duty of care. The defendants denied this plea in their Defence on the basis that the traffic lights were green in favour of the 1st defendant and red against pedestrians: see \[13\] above. Given the defendants’ denial, the legal burden clearly falls on the plaintiff to establish this plea.

### The plaintiff has proven his pleaded account of the collision

24     In my judgment, the plaintiff has proven on the balance of probabilities that at the time of the collision, he was crossing the pedestrian crossing while the pedestrian crossing signal was green. This is for the following reasons.

#### The plaintiff’s consistent evidence that the collision occurred when he was crossing the pedestrian crossing with the green man illuminated

25     At the outset, I note that the plaintiff had consistently maintained, in his contemporaneous documents as well as throughout these proceedings, that the collision occurred when he was crossing the pedestrian crossing with the green man illuminated.

26     In the plaintiff’s police report filed on 25 April 2018, about two and a half weeks after the accident and just a day after he was discharged from KTPH, he reported:

> (a)    under the section “General information of the Accident”, that the location of the accident was “\[a\]long Road 1 Woodlands Avenue 9 Junction of Woodlands Avenue 8 and Avenue 4, _pedestrian crossing_”;[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12)

> (b)    under the section “Details of Person Involved”, that “_Use of Pedestrian Crossing: Used_”;[^13] and

> (c)    under the section “Brief Details”, that “I was at the cross junction of Woodlands Ave wanting to cross of over to avenue 4. _When the traffic light was green for me, I began to cross the road._ Then all of the sudden, I felt a strong impact (unsure from which direction) and I was unconscious right upon the impact.”[^14]

> (emphasis added)

27     In his Statement of Claim and his AEIC, the plaintiff maintained the position taken in his police report that the collision occurred when he was crossing the pedestrian crossing while the green man was illuminated.[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15)

28     The plaintiff’s testimony at trial was consistent with his aforesaid position. Under cross examination, the plaintiff gave evidence that when he reached the pedestrian crossing, the red man was then showing and he waited for about a minute for the traffic lights to change in his favour. During that waiting time, no vehicles entered the Junction from his right from Woodlands Avenue 9: the road was quiet. When the green man came on, he proceeded to cross the Junction at his normal walking pace after ensuring that there were no oncoming vehicles approaching from his right from Woodlands Avenue 9 or making a right turn from Woodlands Avenue 4 onto Woodlands Avenue 9. He had just stepped into the 3rd lane of the road when the collision occurred. He estimated that the collision occurred about three to four seconds after he started crossing the road.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

#### The admission in the Defence that the collision occurred at the pedestrian crossing

29     Secondly, in their Defence, the defendants took the position that the plaintiff was crossing the road at the pedestrian crossing when the collision occurred:

> (a)     In \[1\] of their Defence, the defendants admitted that there was a collision between the plaintiff and the motorcycle “at the place and on the date as stated \[in\] paragraph 1 of the Statement of Claim”. In this regard, paragraph 1 of the Statement of Claim clearly states that “the Plaintiff was crossing the road _at the pedestrian crossing_ … when he was collided into by \[the\] motorcycle”.

> (b)     In the particulars of negligence of the plaintiff set out in \[4\] of their Defence, the defendants asserted as follows:

>> “(a)   failing to keep any or any proper look out for \[the motorcycle\] _when crossing the pedestrian crossing_;

>> (b)    failing to ascertain that traffic was clear _before crossing the pedestrian crossing_;

>> (c)    failing to heed the presence and approach of \[the motorcycle\] which already very close to the pedestrian crossing;

>> (d)     _crossing the road when the traffic lights at the pedestrian crossing was showing red_ against pedestrians;

>> …”

>> \[Emphasis added\]

30     The defendants did not provide any explanation for why they would take such a position in their pleadings if it were untrue.

#### The 1st defendant’s most contemporaneous account of the collision

31     The final piece of evidence which supports the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision is the 1st defendant’s police report filed on 13 April 2018, about a week after the accident. That report was the 1st defendant first written account of the accident. In that report, the 1st defendant simply alleged that at about 9pm that day, he was sending orders to Woods Vale condominium and was travelling along Woodlands Avenue 9 when he met with an accident at the Junction and could not remember what happened next. He made no mention at all that the traffic lights were green in his favour when he entered the Junction, or that the plaintiff did not use the pedestrian crossing to cross the road.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

32     It was only in the 1st defendant’s GIA report dated 24 April 2018 that for the first time, he alleged that the traffic lights were green in his favour and drew a sketch plan depicting the plaintiff crossing the road slightly after the pedestrian crossing.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18) However, I do not find his revised position to be credible for two reasons.

33      _First_, this was not the position taken in the 1st defendant’s police report. In re-examination, the 1st defendant sought to explain this omission in his police report on the basis that it was his first police report and he was inexperienced in making such reports. Thus, he had simply informed the police that he was involved in an accident, and answered their questions which were not many. He did not tell the police the details of the collision because he was unsure of what to do and what to say to the police. He did not prepare his police report himself.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) However, I find this explanation highly unsatisfactory. It suffers from at least two major flaws.

> (a)     One, under cross examination, the 1st defendant testified that he could remember what happened before the collision: it was only what happened after the collision that he could not remember because he lost consciousness in the collision.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) Hence, on his own evidence, he had known, at the time he made his police report, that the traffic lights were in his favour when he entered the Junction and that the plaintiff failed to use the pedestrian crossing to cross the road. Even if this was the first police report he had ever made, a reasonable person in his position would have:

>> (i)       appreciated that it was a crucial detail whether or not the traffic lights were green in his favour when he entered the Junction and the plaintiff had used the pedestrian crossing to cross the road, and

>> (ii)       informed the police that the traffic lights were in his favour and that the plaintiff did not use the pedestrian crossing, if that were truly the case.

> (b)     Two, by virtue of his explanation summarised at \[33\] above, the 1st defendant is asking the Court to believe that:

>> (i)       the police had failed to ask him whether the traffic lights were in his favour when he entered the Junction and whether the plaintiff had used the pedestrian crossing to cross the road; and/or

>> (ii)       even if those questions had been asked and answered, the police failed to record his answers in his police report.

> I find that inconceivable because it would have been crucial, for the police’s investigation into the accident, to find out whether the traffic lights were in the 1st defendant’s favour when he entered the Junction, and whether the plaintiff had used the pedestrian crossing to cross the road. On this note, I do not accept the defendants’ submission that all the crucial information needed by the police is set out in the 39 boxes on the first page of the police report.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) The first page of the police report simply seeks the informant’s particulars, and general information of the accident such as the date, time and location of the accident, the weather and road conditions at the material time and the type of collision.[^22] Such information is clearly insufficient for the police to determine whether road traffic offences have been committed by any of the parties involved in the accident.

34      _Second_, the veracity of the 1st defendant’s sketch plan in his GIA report is suspect for the following reasons:

> (a)     In his sketch plan, the 1st defendant incorrectly depicted the number of lanes along Woodlands Avenue 9 before the Junction. He drew _three_ lanes, wherein the first two lanes were for vehicles going straight across the Junction and the 3rd lane was for vehicles going straight or turning right. However, the Google map photograph in \[3\] of his AEIC and the Google Earth photograph set out at \[4\] above show that there were _four_ lanes along that stretch of the road: the first three lanes were for vehicles going straight across the Junction and the last lane was for vehicles turning right only.

> (b)     When Mr Natverial confronted the 1st defendant on the aforesaid inconsistency between his sketch plan and the Google map photograph in his AEIC, he claimed that the latter was an updated photograph of the road (even though this was _not_ mentioned in his AEIC), and that at the time of the collision, there was no 4th lane for vehicles turning right only. He asserted that he knew this because he has been living in Woodlands and is very familiar with the area.[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) However, his claims are unclearly untrue in light of the Google Earth photograph set out at \[4\] above.

> (c)     In his sketch plan, the 1st defendant drew the alleged position of the vehicle in which the independent eyewitness was seated, namely that the vehicle was _behind_ him and had just started turning right at the Junction from the 3rd lane of Woodlands Avenue 9 into Woodlands Avenue 4. However, the fact that there was an eyewitness to the accident is not a matter within his personal knowledge. It is plain from \[9\] of his AEIC that he only found out about the eyewitness from his supervisor, Mr Chew. In the premises, his sketch plan was clearly embellished in the sense that it contained details which he was not personally aware of, such as the fact that there was apparently an eyewitness to the collision and the alleged position of the eyewitness’s vehicle.

#### The factors relied upon by the defendants to disprove the plaintiff’s pleaded account of the collision

35     In their closing submissions, the defendants contend that the following factors show that the 1st defendant had the right of way:[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24)

> (a)     The 1st defendant did not get into an accident in the Junction with vehicles travelling along Woodlands Avenue 4.

> (b)     No police action was taken against the 1st defendant after they investigated into the accident with the assistance of independent witnesses. The reasonable inference to be drawn from the absence of police action is that the independent witnesses must have given an account of the accident which supported the 1st defendant’s version of the accident (i.e. that the traffic lights were green in favour of him), such that the police concluded that he did not commit any road traffic offence.

36     The defendants also argue that the sketch plan of the accident scene prepared by Sgt Mohamed Fauzy Bin Abdul Aziz (the “Police Sketch Plan”) indicates that the collision had occurred away from the pedestrian crossing as alleged by the 1st defendant. According to the defendants, this conclusion is reached by putting together the following information in the sketch plan:[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25)

> (a)     The distance between the fresh blood stains and the final resting position of the motorcycle was 7.4m. The distance between the blood stains and the pedestrian crossing was much further. Although the actual distance was not stated in the sketch plan, the blood stains could be at least 10m to 15m from the pedestrian crossing.

> (b)     The two short scratch marks that were 3.6m away from the pedestrian crossing were likely not from the motorcycle. Sgt Fauzy could not confirm whether the scratch marks were fresh. Moreover, if the motorcycle had fallen and glided on the ground before ending up at its final resting position, one would expect to see long scratch marks on the road caused by the motorcycle. But that is not the case here.

37     With respect, I am not persuaded by these arguments.

38     It is entirely speculative for the defendants to argue that if the 1st defendant had beaten the red lights at the Junction, he would have gotten into an accident in the Junction with vehicles travelling along Woodlands Avenue 4. While the plaintiff had testified that there was traffic along Woodlands Avenue 4 when he was crossing the pedestrian crossing,[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) neither party gave evidence on how light or heavy the traffic was. Furthermore, regardless of the volume of traffic along Woodlands Avenue 4, I cannot exclude the possibility that any vehicles travelling into the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4 might have seen the 1st defendant’s motorcycle and reacted in time to avoid a collision with him in the Junction.

39     In this regard, I do not give much weight to the plaintiff’s concession during cross examination that if the 1st defendant had entered the Junction when the traffic lights had just turned red against him, he would have gotten into a collision with vehicles moving into the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) It is undisputed that the plaintiff did not see the motorcycle at all.[^28] In the premises, he cannot say with any certainty that the 1st defendant would definitely have gotten into a collision with vehicles travelling along Woodlands Avenue 4 if he had entered the Junction in defiance of the red traffic lights against him.

40     Turning to the absence of police action against the 1st defendant, I do not think that fact assists the defendants. The parties have advanced two opposing theories for why no police action was taken against the 1st defendant: the plaintiff testified that the police had informed him that their investigation was inconclusive as to who was at fault for the accident,[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29) while the defendants submit that the police must have concluded, based on evidence from independent witnesses, that the 1st defendant did not beat the red light. In my view, the plaintiff’s theory is at least as plausible as – if not, more plausible than – the defendants’ theory. If the defendants’ theory is brought to its logical conclusion, one would expect the police to have charged the plaintiff for crossing the road while the traffic lights were red against him and/or failing to yield the right of way to the 1st defendant. However, the fact is that the police did not take any action against any of the parties.

41     More importantly, the police officers who investigated the accident were not called to give evidence on why they did not take action against any of the parties for the accident. In the circumstances, there is no basis for me to infer that the police did not take action against the 1st defendant because they had concluded that he did not beat the red light.

42     As regards the Police Sketch Plan,[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) I note that both parties (and not only the defendants) rely on it to support their respective cases on the location of the collision.[^31] However, I find it to be of no assistance in determining the location of the collision, for the following reasons.

> (a)     While the Police Sketch Plan shows a 1m long fresh blood stain on the road, some distance ahead of the pedestrian crossing, there is no evidence on whether this blood stain was from the plaintiff or the 1st defendant, both of whom were injured in the collision.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32) Sgt Fauzy could not shed light on this issue because by the time he arrived at the accident scene, both the plaintiff or the 1st defendant had already been conveyed to KTPH.[^33] None of the parties’ witnesses were questioned, or gave evidence, on the blood stain.

> (b)     In relation to the two scratch marks that were 3m 6cm away from the pedestrian crossing, it is unclear whether they were from the motorcycle as Sgt Fauzy could not remember whether the scratch marks were fresh.[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34) Even if the scratch marks were from the motorcycle, there is no evidence on how those scratch marks came about. None of the parties’ witnesses were questioned, or gave evidence, on the scratch marks. Neither did the parties call experts in accident reconstruction to explain how the scratch marks (or the fresh blood stain, for that matter) shed light on the location of the collision.

## Issue 2: Whether the 1st defendant was negligent

43     Having found that the plaintiff has proven that he was crossing the pedestrian crossing with the green man illuminated at the time of the collision, I turn to the issue of whether the 1st defendant was negligent.

44     As mentioned at \[15\] above, the defendants concede that the 1st defendant had failed to keep a proper lookout for pedestrians crossing the road and to take evasive action to avoid the collision. My analysis on the issue of the 1st defendant’s negligence is therefore confined to:

> (a)     whether he had failed to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road and to give way to the plaintiff; and

> (b)     whether he had travelled at an excessive speed.

### Whether the 1st defendant had failed to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road and to give way to the plaintiff

45     It is common ground that for the duration that the green man is illuminated at the pedestrian crossing:

> (a)     the traffic lights at the Junction will be red against vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 9.[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) Therefore, pedestrians using the pedestrian crossing will have the right of way pursuant to rule 7 of the Road Traffic (Pedestrian Crossing) Rules (Rev. Ed. 1990) (“Pedestrian Crossing Rules”);[^36] and

> (b)     the traffic lights at the Junction will be green in favour of vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 4, but the green right turn arrow will not light up yet. This means that although vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 4 may turn right into Woodlands Avenue 9, they must give way to pedestrians who are crossing the Junction[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37) pursuant to rule 4 of the Pedestrian Crossing Rules.[^38]

46     Thus, regardless of whether the 1st defendant had entered the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 9 or from Woodlands Avenue 4 turning right into Woodlands Avenue 9, the plaintiff, who was crossing the road while the green man was illuminated, had the right of way.

47     Nonetheless, to be clear, it is my view that the 1st defendant had entered the Junction from the 3rd lane of Woodlands Avenue 9, and not from Woodlands Avenue 4.

> (a)     The 1st defendant had consistently maintained that he was travelling along Woodlands Avenue 9 and was on the way to Woods Vale condominium. He took this position as early as his police report filed on 13 April 2018,[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39) and reiterated this position in his GIA report filed on 24 April 2018,[^40] the Defence,[^41] his AEIC,[^42] and at trial.[^43] In particular, at trial, the 1st defendant marked in red, on exhibit P1, the route he took from the 2nd defendant’s Canadian Pizza outlet to Woods Vale condominium at the time of the accident. The route he marked showed that he had exited from Woodlands Street 81 and went on to Woodlands Avenue 9 before meeting with the accident.[^44]

> (b)     I accept the 1st defendant’s evidence on this subject matter. The 1st defendant had taken a consistent stance on this issue from the outset, and the route he marked on P1 was a plausible one. Moreover, the 1st defendant’s evidence was corroborated by Mr Chew, who testified that the 1st defendant was on a delivery assignment to Woods Vale condominium when the accident happened and that in this regard, the 2nd defendant’s riders are assigned only one location per delivery trip.[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45) There is no objective evidence which contradicted the 1st defendant’s evidence; in fact, the plaintiff admitted that he did not know which direction the 1st defendant had come from[^46]. While the 1st defendant’s police report and his GIA report state that he was sending “_orders_ to Woods Vale condo”, I do not think this shows that he had entered the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4. I accept his explanation that he only had one order of two pizzas to one destination (a unit in Woods Vale condominium), and that he had mistakenly used “orders” in the plural in his reports.[^47]

> (c)     I note that at one juncture in the cross examination, the 1st defendant agreed with Mr Natverial that it was equally possible or more likely that he was travelling on Woodlands Avenue 4 and turning right at the Junction as the traffic lights were green in favour of vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 4.[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) However, this ‘agreement’ must be viewed in the context of his earlier and subsequent testimony that day, where he firmly disagreed on multiple occasions with Mr Natverial’s statements that he had entered the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4.[^49] I therefore give little weight to the said ‘agreement’.

48     Given that the 1st defendant had entered the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 9 when the traffic lights were red against him, he was clearly negligent in failing to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road and to give way to the plaintiff.

### Whether the 1st defendant was travelling at an excessive speed

49     In my view, it is unnecessary to decide whether the 1st defendant was travelling at an excessive speed, in light of my findings below that the plaintiff was not contributorily negligent.

## Issue 3: Whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent

### Whether the plaintiff failed to ascertain that traffic was clear before crossing the road

50     When inquiring into the extent to which preventive measures ought to be taken by a pedestrian at a signalised pedestrian crossing with the traffic lights in his favour, the Highway Code should be the first port of call: see _Asnah bte Ab Rahman v Li Jianlin_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 2 SLR 944</span> (“_Asnah_”) at \[42\].

51     The defendants rely on the following provisions of the Highway Code (1990 Rev Ed) in support of their case that the plaintiff should have ascertained that traffic was clear before crossing the road:[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50)

> (a)     Pursuant to rule 15, the plaintiff should not step onto the pedestrian crossing until he sees a reasonable gap in the traffic.

> (b)     Pursuant to rule 17, the plaintiff should allow approaching vehicles ample time to give way.

52     I am satisfied that the plaintiff had done what was required of him under rules 15 and 17 of the Highway Code.

53     In his AEIC, the plaintiff gave evidence that when he reached the pedestrian crossing, the traffic lights were red against him. He waited for about a minute for the traffic lights to change in his favour. When the green man came on, he proceeded to cross the Junction at his normal walking pace after ensuring that there were no oncoming vehicles.[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51)

54     At the trial, the plaintiff elaborated during cross examination that when the green man came on, he checked to ensure that there were no oncoming vehicles approaching from his right from Woodlands Avenue 9 or making a right turn from Woodlands Avenue 4 onto Woodlands Avenue 9, before he proceeded to cross the Junction. When he looked right, he could see as far as the other end of the Junction. However, he did not see any cars stopping at, or any vehicles on, the other end of the Junction.[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52)

55     I accept the aforesaid evidence of the plaintiff. In my view, it is evident from the following matters that the plaintiff was a reliable witness of truth:

> (a)     The plaintiff displayed candour from the outset. In his police report filed shortly after he was discharged from KTPH, he admitted that he was unsure which direction the impact of the collision came from, and did not know what had hit him: it was IO Mohamed Husnul Taufiq, who visited him on 23 April 2018, who told him that the motorcycle was involved in the collision.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53)

> (b)     At trial, the plaintiff demonstrated the same candour. He gave direct and straightforward responses throughout. He did not attempt to evade counsel for the defendants’ questions, or embellish his answers to buttress his case. To give several examples:

>> (i)       During cross examination, he conceded again that he did not know what hit him or how he was hit.[\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54)

>> (ii)       He readily agreed with counsel for the defendants, Mr Edwin Chua (“Mr Chua”), that it would have been dangerous for the 1st defendant to enter the Junction when the traffic lights had just changed to red against him, and that if the 1stdefendant had done so, he would have gotten into a collision with vehicles entering the Junction from Woodlands Avenue 4.[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) This was despite the fact that his agreement was, on the surface, detrimental to his case that he had crossed the road when the green man was illuminated.

>> (iii)       During re-examination, he testified that he was looking in another direction when he was walking halfway across the road, and therefore did not see which direction the motorcycle came from. If he had seen the motorcycle approaching him, it would have been possible for him to avoid it.[\[note: 56\]](#Ftn_56) He willingly volunteered such evidence even though it could be seized upon by the defendants to bolster their argument that he was contributorily negligent in failing to keep a proper lookout.

56     I reject the defendants’ submission that the motorcycle was surely within the plaintiff’s line of sight (in that he would have seen the headlights of the motorcycle or heard the sound generated by it), and that it was due to his inattentiveness that he failed to see a small vehicle such as the motorcycle.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) None of the defendants’ witnesses gave evidence on whether the headlights of the motorcycle were switched on at the time of the accident, or whether the motorcycle would have generated noise of a level that could be heard by the plaintiff even when it was a distance away from him. Moreover, the plaintiff had testified – and I accept – that he could see as far as the other side of the Junction, but did not see any vehicles: see \[53\] – \[55\] above. In the premises, I find that the motorcycle either was not within the plaintiff’s line of sight, or was simply not visible to the plaintiff, at the time he checked for oncoming vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 9 before crossing the road.

57     Hence, I find that the defendants have not proven that the plaintiff failed to ascertain that traffic was clear before crossing the road.

### Whether the plaintiff failed to keep a proper lookout when crossing the road

58     Turning to what the plaintiff should have done while crossing the road, the defendants rely on rule 19 of the Highway Code.[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58) That rule provides that once on the pedestrian crossing, the plaintiff must look right and left as he crosses, as a driver may not have seen him.

59     The defendants submit that since Woodlands Avenue 9 was a straight road and the plaintiff had testified that he could see as far as the other end of the Junction, the motorcycle would have been within his line of sight if he had kept a proper lookout for oncoming vehicles. He could then have easily avoided the accident by pausing in the middle lane (i.e. the 2nd lane) or taking a few steps back, upon seeing the motorcycle approaching on the 3rd lane.[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59)

60     The crux of this submission is that while crossing the road and prior to stepping onto the 3rd lane, the plaintiff should have checked whether there were any oncoming vehicles approaching from Woodlands Avenue 9. If he had done so, he would have seen the motorcycle approaching him and would have had sufficient time to avoid the motorcycle.

61     It is not disputed that the plaintiff did not conduct such a check: see \[55(b)(iii)\] above. I therefore have to consider:

> (a)     first, whether the plaintiff was required under rule 19 of the Highway Code to conduct such a check; and

> (b)     second, if the plaintiff was required to conduct such a check and had done the check, whether he could have avoided the motorcycle.

62     The first part of this enquiry concerns the proper scope of rule 19. In my view, what rule 19 requires is that while crossing pedestrian crossings, pedestrians should be alert for oncoming traffic _which might be reasonably expected to cross their path_ (emphasis added). I stress the italicised phrase because it is a well settled principle that road users are “not bound to guard against every conceivable eventuality, but only against such eventualities that a reasonable man ought to foresee as being within the ordinary range of human experiences”: see _Asnah_ at \[24\].

63     In the present case, I am not satisfied that it was reasonably foreseeable that the motorcycle would beat the red light and cross the Junction to collide into the plaintiff.

64     It is Mr Fong’s unchallenged evidence that:[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60)

> (a)     During the ‘A’ phase of the operation of the traffic lights at the Junction, the traffic lights facing both directions of Woodlands Avenue 9 would show green for at least 10 seconds, after which it would turn to amber and then to red.

> (b)      _1 second after_ the ‘A’ phase turns to red, the ‘B’ phase would commence. During the “B” phase, the right turn arrow lights allowing vehicles along Woodlands Avenue 9 to turn right into Woodlands Avenue 4 would show green arrow _for at least 7 seconds, after which they would turn flashing for 3 seconds_ before turning off.

> (c)      _3 seconds after_ the “B” phase turns off, the ‘C’ phase and ‘F’ phase would commence, during which the traffic lights facing both directions of Woodlands Avenue 4 and the pedestrian lights allowing pedestrians to walk across both sides of Woodlands Avenue 9 would show green.

> (emphasis added)

65     The implication of Mr Fong’s evidence is that when the plaintiff started crossing the pedestrian crossing, the traffic lights had been red against vehicles travelling along Woodlands Avenue 9 for _at least 14 seconds_. In other words, this was not a situation where the 1st defendant had squeezed past the traffic lights within a few seconds after they had changed against him. The 1st defendant appeared to have wholly oblivious to the traffic lights at the Junction while he was travelling along Woodlands Avenue 9, such that he beat the red light _a very considerable period of time after it had turned red against him_. (emphasis added)

66     The defendants have not adduced any evidence to show that the possibility of vehicles beating a red light, at least 14 seconds after the traffic lights had turned red against them, was a real or reasonably foreseeable one. In the premises, they have failed to prove that the plaintiff did not keep a proper lookout for oncoming vehicles along the 3rd lane (such as the motorcycle) when he was crossing the road.

## Conclusion

67     For the forgoing reasons, I find that the accident was caused wholly by the 1st defendant’s negligence in failing to stop and wait at the Junction until the plaintiff had safely crossed the road, to keep a proper lookout and to take evasive action to avoid the collision. The 2nd defendant is vicariously liable for the 1st defendant’s negligence.

68     Hence, there shall be interlocutory judgment for the plaintiff with damages to be assessed, against both defendants, whose liability shall be joint and several. Costs and interest are reserved to the trial judge assessing the damages.
